[normal]ANNEX B[bold]Relevant legislation for England and Wales[bold]Representation of the People Act 1983
[normal]7A Residence: persons remanded in custody etc[bold](1) This section applies to a person who is detained at any place pursuant to a relevant order or direction and is so detained otherwise than after—
[normal](a) 
[normal]being
[normal] convicted of any offence, or
[normal](b) 
[normal]a
[normal] finding in criminal proceedings that he did the act or made the omission charged.
[normal](2) 
[normal]A person to whom this section applies shall (subject to subsection (5) below) be regarded for the purposes of section 4 above
[normal] [
[normal]section 4 is the general entitlement to be registered as a parliamentary or local government elector if on the relevant date he or she is resident in the constituency etc
[normal]] 
[normal]as resident at the place at which he is detained if the length of the period which he is likely to spend at that place is sufficient for him to be regarded as being resident there for the purposes of electoral registration
[normal].
[normal](3) A person registered in a register of electors in pursuance of an application for registration made by virtue of subsection (2) above is entitled to remain so registered until—
[normal](a) 
[normal]the
[normal] end of the period of 12 months beginning with the date when the entry in the register first takes effect, or
[normal](
[normal]aa
[normal]) the registration officer determines in accordance with regulations that the person was not entitled to be registered, or
[normal](
[normal]ab
[normal]) the registration officer determines in accordance with regulations that the person was registered as the result of an application under section 10ZC made by some other person or that the person's entry has been altered as the result of an application under section 10ZD made by some other person, or
[normal](b) 
[normal]another
[normal] entry made in respect of him in any register of electors takes effect (whether or not in pursuance of an application made by virtue of subsection (2)),
[normal]whichever
[normal] first occurs.
[normal](4) Where the entitlement of such a person to remain so registered terminates by virtue of subsection (3) above, the registration officer concerned shall remove that person's entry from the register, unless he is entitled to remain registered in pursuance of a further application made by virtue of subsection (2).
[normal](5) Subsection (2) above shall not be taken as precluding the registration of a person to whom this section applies—
[normal](a) 
[normal]by
[normal] virtue of his residence at some place other than the place at which he is detained, or
[normal](b) 
[normal]in
[normal] pursuance of a declaration of local connection.
[normal](6) In this section “a relevant order or direction” means—
[normal](a) 
[normal]a
[normal] remand or committal in custody;
[normal](b) a remand to a hospital under 
[normal]section 35
[normal] or 
[normal]36
[normal] of the Mental Health Act 1983 or Article 42 or 43 of the Mental Health (Northern Ireland) Order 1986;
[normal](c) 
[normal]a
[normal] direction for removal to a hospital under section 48 of that Act or Article 54 of that Order;
[normal](d) 
[normal]an
[normal] assessment order under section 52D or a treatment order under section 52M of the 
[normal]Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995
[normal]; or
[normal][(e) a transfer for treatment direction under 
[normal]section 136
[normal] of the Mental Health (Care and Treatment) (Scotland) Act 2003 made in respect of a person to whom that section applies by virtue of article 13 of the 
[normal]Mental Health (Care and Treatment) (Scotland) Act 2003
[normal] (Consequential Provisions) Order 2005].]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7B Notional residence: declarations of local connection[bold](1) A declaration under this section (“a declaration of local connection”)—
[normal](a) 
[normal]may
[normal] be made only by a person to whom this section applies, but
[normal](b) 
[normal]may
[normal] be made by such a person despite the fact that by reason of his age he is not entitled to vote.
[normal](2) This section applies to any person who on the date when he makes such a declaration is—
[normal](a) a person to whom section 7 above applies and who would not be entitled to be registered by virtue of residence at any place other than the mental hospital (within the meaning of that section) at which he is a patient, or
[normal](b) a person to whom section 7A applies and who would not be entitled to be registered by virtue of residence at any place other than the place at which he is detained as mentioned in subsection (1) of that section, or
[normal](c) a person who does not fall within paragraph (a) or (b) above (and is not otherwise in legal custody) and who is not, for the purposes of section 4 above, resident at any address in the United Kingdom (a “homeless person”).
[normal](3) A declaration of local connection shall state—
[normal](a) 
[normal]the
[normal] name of the 
[normal]declarant
[normal] and either—
[normal](
[normal]i
[normal]) an address to which correspondence for him from either the registration officer concerned or the returning officer can be delivered, or
[normal](ii) 
[normal]that
[normal] he is willing to collect such correspondence periodically from the registration officer's office;
[normal](b) 
[normal]the
[normal] date of the declaration;
[normal](c) 
[normal]that
[normal] on the date of the declaration the 
[normal]declarant
[normal] falls into one of the categories of persons to whom this section applies, specifying—
[normal](
[normal]i
[normal]) 
[normal]the
[normal] category in question, and
[normal](ii) (
[normal]in
[normal] the case of a person falling within subsection (2)(a) or (b) above) the name and address of the mental hospital at which he is a patient or (as the case may be) of the place at which he is detained;
[normal](d) 
[normal]the
[normal] required address (as defined by subsection (4) below);
[normal](e) 
[normal]that
[normal] on the date of the declaration the 
[normal]declarant
[normal] is a Commonwealth citizen or a citizen of the Republic of Ireland or (if the declaration is made for the purposes only of local government elections) a relevant citizen of the Union;
[normal](f) 
[normal]whether
[normal] the 
[normal]declarant
[normal] has on the date of the declaration attained the age of 18 years, and, if he has not, the date of his birth.
[normal](4) For the purposes of this section “the required address” is—
[normal](a) 
[normal]in
[normal] the case of a person falling within subsection (2)(a) or (b) above—
[normal](
[normal]i
[normal]) the address in the United Kingdom where he would be residing if he were not such a patient, or detained, as mentioned in that provision, or
[normal](ii) 
[normal]if
[normal] he cannot give such an address, an address in the United Kingdom at which he has resided;
[normal](b) in the case of a homeless person, the address of, or which is nearest to, a place in the United Kingdom where he commonly spends a substantial part of his time (whether during the day or at night).
[normal](5) Where a declaration of local connection is made for the purposes of registration in Northern Ireland, the declaration must state that the 
[normal]declarant
[normal] has been in Northern Ireland during the whole of the period of three months ending on the date of the declaration.
[normal](6) Where a declaration of local connection made by a homeless person is delivered to the registration officer concerned during the period—
[normal](a) 
[normal]beginning
[normal] with the date when a vacancy occurs—
[normal](
[normal]i
[normal]) 
[normal]in
[normal] the seat for the parliamentary constituency within which the required address falls, or
[normal](ii) 
[normal]in
[normal] the seat for any Scottish Parliament constituency or National Assembly for Wales constituency within which it falls, and
[normal](b) ending on the final nomination day (within the meaning of section 13B below) for the parliamentary by-election, or (as the case may be) the election under 
[normal]section 9
[normal] of the Scotland Act 1998 or [
[normal]section 10
[normal] of the Government of Wales Act 2006], held in respect of that vacancy,
[normal]the
[normal] declaration must state that, during the period of three months ending on the date of the declaration, the 
[normal]declarant
[normal] has commonly been spending a substantial part of his time (whether during the day or at night) at, or near, the required address.
[normal](7) No declaration of local connection shall be specially made by a person for the purposes of local government elections, and any such declaration made for the purposes of parliamentary elections shall have effect also for the purposes of local government elections; but—
[normal](a) a declaration of local connection may be made for the purposes only of local government elections by a person who is as a peer subject to a legal incapacity to vote at parliamentary elections or by a relevant citizen of the Union; and
[normal](b) 
[normal]where
[normal] so made, shall be marked to show that it is available for local government elections only, but shall in all other respects be the same as other declarations of local connection.
[normal](8) If a person—
[normal](a) 
[normal]makes
[normal] a declaration of local connection stating more than one address under subsection (3)(d) above, or
[normal](b) 
[normal]makes
[normal] more than one declaration of local connection bearing the same date and stating different addresses under that provision,
[normal]the
[normal] declaration or declarations shall be void.
[normal](9) A declaration of local connection may be cancelled at any time by the 
[normal]declarant
[normal].
[normal](10) A declaration of local connection shall be of no effect unless it is received by the registration officer concerned within the period of three months beginning with the date of the declaration.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7C Effect of declaration of local connection[bold](1) Where a person's declaration of local connection is in force when he applies for registration, he shall be regarded for the purposes of section 4 above as—
[normal](
[normal]a
[normal]) resident on the date of the declaration at the address stated in it in accordance with section 7B(3)(d) above; and
[normal](b) for the purposes of registration in Northern Ireland, as resident in Northern Ireland during the whole of the period of three months ending with that date.
[normal](2) A person registered in a register of electors in pursuance of a declaration of local connection is entitled to remain so registered until—
[normal](a) 
[normal]the
[normal] end of the period of 12 months beginning with the date when the entry in the register first takes effect,
[normal](
[normal]aa
[normal]) the registration officer determines in accordance with regulations that the person was not entitled to be registered,
[normal](
[normal]ab
[normal]) the registration officer determines in accordance with regulations that the person was registered as the result of an application under section 10ZC made by some other person or that the person's entry has been altered as the result of an application under section 10ZD made by some other person,
[normal](b) 
[normal]the
[normal] declaration is cancelled under section 7B(9) above, or
[normal](c) 
[normal]another
[normal] entry made in respect of him in any register of electors takes effect (whether or not in pursuance of a declaration of local connection),
[normal]whichever
[normal] first occurs.
[normal](3) Where the entitlement of such a person to remain so registered terminates by virtue of subsection (2) above, the registration officer concerned shall remove that person's entry from the register, unless he is entitled to remain registered in pursuance of a further declaration of local connection.
[normal](4) This section shall not be taken as precluding the registration of a person falling within section 7B(2)(a) or (b) above in pursuance of an application made by virtue of section 7(2) or 7A(2) above.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Representation of the People Act 2000
[normal]Schedule 4 to the Representation of the People Act 2000 makes provision with respect to the manner of voting at elections, in particular absent voting in parliamentary and local government elections in England, Wales and Scotland (see section 12 RPA 2000).  Paragraph 2 of Schedule 4 provides:
[normal]Manner of voting at parliamentary or local government elections[bold]2[bold](1) This paragraph applies to determine the manner of voting of a person entitled to vote as an elector at a parliamentary or local government election.
[normal](2) He may vote in person at the polling station allotted to him under the appropriate rules, unless he is entitled as an elector to an absent vote at the election.
[normal](3) He may vote by post if he is entitled as an elector to vote by post at the election.
[normal](4) If he is entitled to vote by proxy at the election, he may so vote unless, before a ballot paper has been issued for him to vote by proxy, he applies at the polling station allotted to him under the appropriate rules for a ballot paper for the purpose of voting in person, in which case he may vote in person there.
[normal]…
[normal](6) Nothing in the preceding provisions of this paragraph applies to—
[normal](a) . . .
[normal](b) 
[normal]a
[normal] person to whom section 7A of that Act (persons remanded in custody) applies,
[normal]whether he is registered by virtue of that provision or not; and such a person may only vote by post or by proxy (where he is entitled as an elector to vote by post or, as the case may be, by proxy at the election)
[normal].
[normal][(6A) Sub-paragraph (2) above does not prevent a person, at the polling station allotted to him, marking a tendered ballot paper in pursuance of rule 40(1ZC) or (1ZE) of the parliamentary elections rules.]
[normal][(6B) Sub-paragraph (2) above does not prevent a person, at the polling station allotted to him at a local government election in Scotland, marking a tendered ballot paper in pursuance of any provision—
[normal](a) 
[normal]made
[normal] under 
[normal]section 3(1)
[normal] of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004 (asp 9) as to the conduct of elections of councillors, and
[normal](b) 
[normal]which
[normal] entitles him to do so despite the fact that he is or may be entitled to an absent vote at the election.]
[normal](7) For the purposes of the provisions of—
[normal](a) 
[normal]this
[normal] Schedule, and
[normal](b) 
[normal]the
[normal] 1983 Act so far as it has effect in relation to England, Wales and Scotland,
[normal]a person entitled to vote as an elector at a parliamentary or local government election is entitled as an elector to vote by post or entitled to vote by proxy at the election [if sub-paragraph (8) or (9) (as the case may be) applies to him in relation to the election]; and references in those provisions to entitlement as an elector to an absent vote at a parliamentary or local government election are references to entitlement as an elector to vote by post or entitlement to vote by proxy at the election.
[normal][(8) This sub-paragraph applies to a person who is shown in the postal voters list mentioned in paragraph 5(2) below as entitled to vote by post at an election.
[normal](9) This sub-paragraph applies to a person who is shown in the list of proxies mentioned in paragraph 5(3) below as entitled to vote by proxy at an election.
